{"title_page": "Lurene Tuttle", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress and acting coach}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Lurene Tuttle\n| image        = Lurene Tuttle 1947.jpg\n| caption      = Tuttle in 1947\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1907|8|29}}\n| birth_place  = [[Pleasant Lake, Indiana]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1986|5|28|1907|8|29}}\n| death_place  = [[Encino, Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Glendale]]\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1934\u20131986\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Melville Ruick]]<br>|1928|1945|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Frederick W. Cole<br>|1950|1956|end=divorced}}\n| children = [[Barbara Ruick]]\n| relatives = [[Joseph Williams (musician)|Joseph Williams]] (grandson)\n}}\n\n'''Lurene Tuttle''' (August 29, 1907 \u2013 May 28, 1986) was an American character actress and acting coach, who made the transition from [[vaudeville]] to radio, and later films and television. Her most enduring impact was as one of network radio's more versatile actresses. Often appearing in 15 shows per week,<ref name=nyt/> comedies, dramas, thrillers, soap operas, and crime dramas, she became known as the \"First Lady of Radio\".\n\n==Early years==\nTuttle was born August 29, 1907, at Pleasant Lake, Indiana into a family with strong ties to entertainment. Her father, Clair Vivien Tuttle (1883\u20131950), had been a performer in [[minstrel show]]s before becoming a station agent for a railroad. Her grandfather, Frank Tuttle, managed an opera house and taught drama. Her mother was Verna Sylvia (Long) Tuttle. She discovered her own knack for acting after moving with her family to Glendale, Arizona. She later credited a drama coach there for \"making me aware of life as it really is\u2014by making me study life in real situations.\"<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last1=Thackrey|first1=Ted Jr.|title=Character Actress Lurene Tuttle, 78, Dies|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-05-30/local/me-8342_1_lurene-tuttle|accessdate=31 August 2015|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=May 30, 1986}}</ref>\n\nAfter her family moved to Southern California, Tuttle appeared in productions at the [[Pasadena Playhouse]], then joined the [[vaudeville]] troupe Murphy's Comedians. By the time of the [[Great Depression]], Tuttle had put her vocal versatility to work in radio, and within a decade, she became an in-demand actress in the medium.\n\n==Radio roles==\nTuttle's radio debut came in 1936 when she appeared on ''[[Hollywood Hotel (radio program)|Hollywood Hotel]]'' with [[Dick Powell]].<ref name=lat/> Despite having never performed before a microphone, Tuttle's audition won her a three-year contract with the program.<ref name=rtm847>{{cite journal|last1=Tuttle|first1=Lurene|title=Luck Is Hard Work|journal=Radio Mirror|date=August 1947|volume=28|issue=3|pages=20\u201321, 81\u201382|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Mirror/47/Mirror-1947-Aug.pdf|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThirteen years later, one newspaper columnist called her \"quite possibly the most-heard woman in America.\"<ref name=hn>{{cite news|last1=Handsaker|first1=Gene|title=Lurene Tuttle Probably Most-Heard Woman in U. S.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3131352/the_hutchinson_news/|agency=The Hutchinson News|date=October 26, 1949|page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 31, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nOn radio's ''[[The Adventures of Sam Spade]]'' she played just about every female role as well as Spade's secretary Effie Perrine.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|title=Lurene Tuttle, 79, an Actress In Films and on Radio and TV|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/05/31/obituaries/lurene-tuttle-79-an-actress-in-films-and-on-radio-and-tv.html|accessdate=31 August 2015|agency=New York Times|date=May 31, 1986}}</ref> She appeared in such shows as ''[[The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet]]'' and concurrently appeared on ''[[The Great Gildersleeve]]'' as the niece Marjorie Forrester. Tuttle had regular roles in such shows as ''Brenthouse'',<ref name=\"dunningota\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn |url-access=registration |quote=Brenthouse, serial drama. |last=Dunning |first=John |authorlink=John Dunning (detective fiction author) |title=On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio| date=1998| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=New York, NY| isbn=978-0-19-507678-3| page=[https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn/page/118 118] | edition=Revised| accessdate=2019-09-25}}</ref> ''[[Dr. Christian]]'', ''[[Duffy's Tavern]]'', ''[[One Man's Family]]'', ''[[The Raleigh Cigarette Program#The Red Skelton Show|The Red Skelton Show]]'' (as Junior's mother and as Daisy June, roles that she shared with Harriet Nelson), ''[[Hollywood Hotel (radio program)|Hollywood Hotel]]'', and ''Those We Love''.\n\n''[[Dr. Christian]]'' was unusual in that the show, according to critic [[Leonard Maltin]] in ''The Great American Broadcast: A Celebration of Radio's Golden Age'', solicited scripts from listeners (one of whom was a young [[Rod Serling]]) and put them on the air\u2014with a little help. Tuttle recalled:\n\n<blockquote>The real writers on the show had to fix them quite often a lot, because they were really quite amateurish. But they had nice thoughts, they had nice plots. They just needed fixing; the dialogue didn't work too well.</blockquote>\n\nTuttle guest starred on the radio police series ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]'', starring [[Jack Webb]], ''[[Lux Radio Theater]]'', ''[[The Screen Guild Theater]]'' and ''[[Suspense]]'', in the episode \"The Sisters\", with [[Rosalind Russell]]. In ''[[The Whistler]]'', she played good and evil twins and used separate microphones to stay in character for each twin.\n\nIt was during her time on ''Hollywood Hotel'' that Tuttle became involved in the founding of the [[American Federation of Television and Radio Artists|American Federation of Radio Artists]]. According to Maltin, Tuttle's male counterpart on the show, veteran actor [[Frank Nelson (actor)|Frank Nelson]] (a frequent guest performer on [[Jack Benny]]'s program), tried to get both a raise to $35 per show\u2014at a time when the show paid $5,000 per appearance to headlining guest stars. Nelson eventually got the raises, but the negotiations prompted him to become an AFRA co-founder and one of its active members.\n\nTuttle later became the first female president of the federation's Hollywood local.<ref name=lat/>\n\nTuttle also remembered the day the ''Hollywood Hotel'' sound effects man was upstaged by a Hollywood legend:\n\n<blockquote>The soundman was supposed to do a little yipping, yappy dog, like a terrier. He sounded like a Newfoundland dog or something, and the director kept saying \"That won't do.\" So [[Olivia de Havilland]] was sitting next to me, and she says \"I can do a very good dog.\" And I said \"Well, I don't think they'll let you do a dog. This is an audience show; you're a star, you can't do a dog.\" And Olivia says \"I'm going to do it.\" So she went over to the director, went into the booth and said \"I'd like to try doing this dog for you.\" So they put her behind the screen, and she went on the show and she did that yipping dog.\"</blockquote>\n\n== Films and television ==\nTuttle became a familiar face to millions of television viewers with more than 100 appearances from 1950 to 1986, often in the role of an inquisitive busybody. On television and in films, Tuttle streamlined herself into a pattern of roles between wise, loving wives/mothers or bristling matrons. She was familiar to the early television audience as wife/mother Lavinia (Vinnie) Day in ''[[Life with Father#Television series|Life with Father]]'' (1953\u20131955). Columnist [[Hedda Hopper]] called the selection of [[Leon Ames]] as Father and Tuttle as Mother \"what I consider 22 carat casting with two all-Americans.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hopper|first1=Hedda|title=Producer Crosses Sea to Sign Cary Grant|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1953/10/07/page/38/article/looking-at-hollywood|accessdate=1 September 2015|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=October 7, 1953|page=Part 3, Page 6}}</ref>\n\n''[[Heaven Only Knows (1947 film)|Heaven Only Knows]]'' (1947) was her first film.<ref name=lat/> She went on to roles in other films such as [[Orson Welles]]'s ''[[Macbeth (1948 film)|Macbeth]]'' (1948), ''[[Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House]]'' (1948) and [[Alfred Hitchcock|Alfred Hitchcock's]] ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960), as the wife of Sheriff Chambers. In ''[[Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1952) she portrayed a mother who lets a disturbed [[Marilyn Monroe]] babysit her daughter. The next year she appeared again with Marilyn in ''[[Niagara (film)|Niagara]]'', as Mrs. Kettering. She had a rare starring role in ''[[Ma Barker's Killer Brood]]'' (1960). She played Grandma Pusser in the original ''[[Walking Tall (1973 film)|Walking Tall]]'' film trilogy, and also appeared in horror films such as ''[[The Manitou]]'' (1978), starring [[Tony Curtis]]. Her final film role was in the 1983 film ''[[Testament (1983 film)|Testament]]''.\n\nShe guest-starred twice on [[Edmond O'Brien]]'s 1960 crime drama ''[[Johnny Midnight (TV series)|Johnny Midnight]]''. She then played a supporting role in the 1961 ''[[Father of the Bride (TV series)|Father of the Bride]]'' television [[situation comedy]]. She made six guest appearances on ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', with [[Raymond Burr]], during the nine-year run of the show from 1957 to 1966. She usually played the role of the defendant, such as Anna Houser in \"The Case of the Substitute Face\" in 1958, Sarette Winslow in \"The Case of the Artful Dodger\" in 1959, Sarah Breel in \"The Case of the Shoplifter's Shoe\" in 1963, and Josephine Kempton in \"The Case of the Grinning Gorilla\" in 1965. However, in 1966 she played the role of murderess Henny McLeod in \"The Case of the Avenging Angel.\"\n\nIn 1958 and 1959, she was cast in two episodes as Gladys Purvis, the mother of series character Kate McCoy, played by [[Kathleen Nolan]], in the sitcom ''[[The Real McCoys]]'', with [[Walter Brennan]] and [[Richard Crenna]].<ref name=imdb>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0878354/|title=Lurene Tuttle|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref> She appeared twice on the NBC western series ''[[The Californians (TV series)|The Californians]]'', once as Belle Calhoun in \"Skeleton in the Closet\" (1958) and then as Maude Sorel in \"The Painted Lady\" (1959). She guest-starred with [[Andrew Duggan]] in his crime series ''[[Bourbon Street Beat]]''.\n\nTuttle appeared three times each on sitcoms ''[[The Danny Thomas Show]]'' and ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'' and twice on the following: ''[[Leave It to Beaver]]'', ''[[The Bob Cummings Show]]'', ''[[The Ann Sothern Show]]'', ''[[Pete and Gladys]]'', ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'', ''[[Hazel (TV series)|Hazel]]'', ''[[General Electric Theater]]'', ''[[Switch (TV series)|Switch]]'', and ''[[Fantasy Island (1977 TV series)|Fantasy Island]]''. \n \nIn 1960, she was cast as Mrs. Courtland in the episode \"The Raffle Ticket\" of the sitcom based on the [[comic strip]] ''[[Dennis the Menace (1959 TV series)|Dennis the Menace]]'', with [[Jay North]] and [[Joseph Kearns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0557993/|title=The Raffle Ticket'', ''Dennis the Menace'', December 18, 1960|publisher=Internet Movie Data Base|accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTuttle guest-starred in such westerns as ''[[Buckskin (TV series)|Buckskin]]'', ''[[The Restless Gun]]'', ''[[Colt .45 (TV series)|Colt .45]]'', ''[[Johnny Ringo (TV series)|Johnny Ringo]]'' as well as ''[[The Cowboys (TV series)|The Cowboys]]'', ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'', ''[[Bonanza]]'', ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Jim Bowie]]'', ''[[Lawman (TV series)|Lawman]]'', and ''[[The Iron Horse (TV series)|The Iron Horse]].''<ref name=imdb/>\n\nTuttle was cast as Mrs. Grange in the 1963 episode \"The Risk\" on the drama series ''[[Mr. Novak]]'', starring [[James Franciscus]] as an idealistic high school teacher. She later appeared on the popular 1960s sitcoms ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'', ''[[The Munsters]]'', and ''[[Petticoat Junction]]''.\n\nTuttle's best-known role to the general public was in 32 episodes of the series ''[[Julia (TV series)|Julia]]'' (1968\u20131971) as the humorless but warm-hearted Hannah Yarby.<ref name=imdb/>\n\nIn 1972, she appeared as Bella Swann on the episode \"Farmer Ted and the News\" on \"The Mary Tyler Moore Show\" and as Mrs. Sharp on \"The Partridge Family\"\nthat same year.\n\nIn 1980, Tuttle appeared as Mrs. McIntyre in the television movie ''[[White Mama]]'', with [[Bette Davis]].<ref name=\"imdb\" /> From 1981 to 1984, Tuttle appeared six times on the drama series ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]''\n\nIn 1985, Tuttle appeared in episode 25 (\"Murder in the Afternoon\") of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', playing the character Agnes Cochran, Jessica Fletcher's aunt.  The episode first aired on October 13, 1985.\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 1944, Tuttle received Radio Life magazine's Distinguished Achievement Award for Best Supporting Feminine Player.<ref>{{cite news|title=Distinguished Achievement Awards|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/Archive-Radio-Life-IDX/IDX/Radio-Life-1944-04-09-OCR-Page-0014.pdf|accessdate=1 September 2015|agency=Radio Life|date=April 9, 1944}}</ref>\n\nTuttle has two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] \u2013 \"Star of Radio\" at 1760 Vine Street and \"Star of Television\" at 7011 Hollywood Boulevard. Both stars were dedicated February 8, 1960.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lurene Tuttle|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/lurene-tuttle|website=Hollywood Walk of Fame|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life ==\nTuttle married [[Melville Ruick]], an actor whom she had met during her radio years; the couple had a daughter, [[Barbara Ruick]],.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mother and Daughter Suggest Beauty Tips|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3124933/the_paris_news/|agency=The Paris News|date=December 19, 1955|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 30, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> Tuttle and Ruick eventually divorced. She married Frederick W. Cole, an engineer, on November 27, 1950 in Pasadena, California; she sued him for divorce on January 4, 1956.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lurene Tuttle Sues for Divorce|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3131273/long_beach_independent/|agency=Long Beach Independent|date=January 5, 1956|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 31, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> Daughter Barbara Ruick, 43, who was married to film composer [[John Williams]], died of a cerebral hemorrhage while on film location in 1974.\n\nShe became a respected acting coach and teacher\u2014something she had always done, even at the height of her acting career (she often re-trained radio actors who had been away from the craft during service in World War II).\n\nTuttle had a hobby of collecting toy dogs. A 1930 newspaper article reported \"Her dressing room shelf is filled with more than 200 miniature replicas of every variety of dog known.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Toy Dogs, Not Real Ones, Are Actress' Hobby|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3131496/oakland_tribune/|agency=Oakland Tribune|date=May 6, 1930|page=27|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 31, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nTuttle, a registered [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], campaigned for [[Dwight Eisenhower]] in the [[1952 United States presidential election|1952 presidential election]].<ref>''Motion Picture and Television Magazine'', November 1952, page 34, Ideal Publishers </ref>\n\n==Death==\nTuttle died from cancer May 28, 1986 at Encino Hospital. Memorial services were held June 2, 1986 at Church of the Recessional at Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Glendale.<ref name=lat/>\n\nHer ''Sam Spade'' co-star [[Howard Duff]], who delivered her eulogy, remembered Tuttle:\n\n<blockquote>She could just take hold of a part and do something with it...I think she never met a part she didn't like. She just loved to work; she loved to act. She's a woman who was born to do what she was doing and loved every minute of it.</blockquote>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{div col}}\n*''[[Stand Up and Cheer!]]'' (1934) \u2013 Stenographer (uncredited)\n*''[[Tom, Dick and Harry (1941 film)|Tom, Dick and Harry]]'' (1941) \u2013 Girl Lead in Movie (voice, uncredited)\n*''[[Heaven Only Knows (1947 film)|Heaven Only Knows]]'' (1947) \u2013 Mrs. O'Donnell\n*''[[Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House]]'' (1948) \u2013 Mary\n*''[[Homecoming (1948 film)|Homecoming]]'' (1948) \u2013 Miss Stoker\n*''[[Macbeth (1948 film)|Macbeth]]'' (1948) \u2013 Gentlewoman / The Three\n*''[[The Admiral Was a Lady]]'' (1950) \u2013 Ethyl \u2013 Unemployment Clerk (uncredited)\n*''[[A Life of Her Own]]'' (1950) \u2013 Secretary (uncredited)\n*''[[Watch the Birdie (1950 film)|Watch the Birdie]]'' (1950) \u2013 Millie (uncredited)\n*''[[Goodbye, My Fancy]]'' (1951) \u2013 Ellen Griswold\n*''[[Tomorrow Is Another Day (1951 American film)|Tomorrow Is Another Day]]'' (1951) \u2013 Stella Dawson\n*''[[The Whip Hand]]'' (1951) \u2013 Molly Loomis\n*''[[Room for One More (film)|Room for One More]]'' (1952) \u2013 Miss Kenyon\n*''[[Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1952) \u2013 Ruth Jones\n*''[[Niagara (film)|Niagara]]'' (1953) \u2013 Mrs. Kettering\n*''[[Never Wave at a WAC]]'' (1953) \u2013 Capt. Murchinson, Company CO\n*''[[The Affairs of Dobie Gillis]]'' (1953) \u2013 Mrs. Eleanor Hammer\n*''[[Give a Girl a Break]]'' (1953) \u2013 Mrs. Doolittle\n*''[[The Glass Slipper]]'' (1955) \u2013 Cousin Loulou\n*''[[Sincerely Yours (film)|Sincerely Yours]]'' (1955) \u2013 Mrs. McGinley\n*''[[Slander (1956 film)|Slander]]'' (1957) \u2013 Mrs. Doyle\n*''[[Untamed Youth]]'' (1957) \u2013 Judge Cecilia Steele Tropp\n*''[[Sweet Smell of Success]]'' (1957) \u2013 Loretta Bartha (uncredited)\n*''[[Ma Barker's Killer Brood]]'' (1960) \u2013 Ma Barker\n*''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960) \u2013 Mrs. Chambers\n*''[[Critic's Choice (film)|Critic's Choice]]'' (1963) \u2013 Mother in \"Sisters Three\"\n*''[[Nightmare in the Sun]]'' (1965) \u2013 Gideon's wife\n*''The Restless Ones'' (1965)\n*''[[The Ghost and Mr. Chicken]]'' (1966) \u2013 Mrs. Natalie Miller\n*''[[The Fortune Cookie]]'' (1966) \u2013 Mother Hinkle\n*''[[The Horse in the Gray Flannel Suit]]'' (1968) \u2013 Aunt Martha\n*''[[Walking Tall (1973 film)|Walking Tall]]'' (1973) \u2013 Grandma\n*''Dirty Duck'' (1974) \u2013 Duck's Mother (voice)\n*''[[Walking Tall Part 2]]'' (1975) \u2013 Grandma Pusser\n*''The World Through the Eyes of Children'' (1975) \u2013 Tuttle\n*''[[Evil Town]]'' (1977) \u2013 Mildred Phelps\n*''[[Walking Tall: Final Chapter]]'' (1977) \u2013 Grandma Pusser\n*''[[The Manitou]]'' (1978) \u2013 Mrs. Herz\n*''The Story of Heidi'' (1979) - Clara's Grandmother (voice)\n*''[[Nutcracker Fantasy]]'' (1979) \u2013 Aunt Gerda (voice)\n*''[[Parts: The Clonus Horror]]'' (1979) \u2013 Anna Noble\n*''[[Human Experiments]]'' (1979) \u2013 Granny\n*''[[White Mama]]'' (1980) \u2013 Mrs. McIntyre\n*''[[Return of the Beverly Hillbillies]]'' (1981) \u2013 Mollie Heller\n*''[[Testament (1983 film)|Testament]]'' (1983) \u2013 Rosemary Abhart\n*''[[It Came Upon the Midnight Clear (film)|It Came Upon the Midnight Clear]]'' (1984) \u2013 Mrs. Hunt\n{{div col end}}\n\nShe also played the part of Eddie Haskell's landlady in ''[[Leave It to Beaver]]''{{'}}s 1962 episode called \"Bachelor at Large\".\n\n== Records ==\nTuttle played the swallow in \"[[The Happy Prince (Orson Welles, Bing Crosby album)|The Happy Prince]]\", an adaption of Oscar Wilde's short story with [[Orson Welles]] and [[Bing Crosby]] (1946). The story had been adapted for radio by Orson Welles in 1944, featuring a musical score by [[Bernard Herrmann]]. It aired on the Philco Radio Hall of Fame broadcast on December 24, 1944<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pairpoint|first1=Lionel|title=And Here's Bing|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/afrs.htm#sundry46|website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> with Lureen Tuttle playing The Swallow and featuring Bing Crosby alongside Orson Welles, with Herrmann's music conducted by [[Victor Young]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Indiana|California|Theatre|Radio|Film|Television}}\n\n==References==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== General references ===\n* Frank Buxton and Bill Owen, ''The Big Broadcast 1920\u20131950''.\n* Leonard Maltin, ''The Great American Broadcast: A Celebration of Radio's Golden Age''. New York: Dutton, 1997.\n* [[Gerald Nachman (journalist)|Gerald Nachman]], ''Raised on Radio''. New York: Pantheon, 1998.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p4.cgi?ArtistName=Tuttle,%20Lurene&ArtistNumber=29861 From radioGOLDINdex: a partial list of radio programs in which Lurene Tuttle appeared]\n* {{IMDb name|878354}}\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0DE1D61F3EF932A05756C0A960948260 ''New York Times'' obituary]\n\n=== Audio ===\n* [https://archive.org/download/GG_S_01/GG_1941-09-07_ep002_Marjories_Cake.mp3 ''The Great Gildersleeve'', \"Marjorie's Cake\" (7 September 1941)]\n* [https://archive.org/download/OTRR_The_Adventures_of_Sam_Spade_Singles/SamSpade_48-08-01_110_TheDryMartiniCaper_CBS.mp3 ''The Adventures of Sam Spade'', \"The Dry Martini Caper\" (1 August 1948)]\n* [https://archive.org/download/suspenseOTRKIBM001/Suspense-460725CANTWEBEFRIENDS.mp3 ''Suspense'', \"Can't We Be Friends?\"] (25 July 1946)\n* [https://archive.org/download/suspenseOTRKIBM002/Suspense-481209TheSisters.mp3 ''Suspense'', \"The Sisters\"] (with Rosalind Russell, 9 December 1948)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuttle, Lurene}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Indiana]]\n[[Category:American radio actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Indiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Steuben County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress and acting coach}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Lurene Tuttle\n| image        = Lurene Tuttle 1947.jpg\n| caption      = Tuttle in 1947\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1907|8|29}}\n| birth_place  = [[Pleasant Lake, Indiana]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1986|5|28|1907|8|29}}\n| death_place  = [[Encino, Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Glendale]]\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1934\u20131986\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Melville Ruick]]<br>|1928|1945|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Frederick W. Cole<br>|1950|1956|end=divorced}}\n| children = [[Barbara Ruick]]\n| relatives = [[Joseph Williams (musician)|Joseph Williams]] (grandson)\n}}\n\n'''Lurene Tuttle''' (August 29, 1907 \u2013 May 28, 1986) was an American character actress and acting coach, who made the transition from [[vaudeville]] to radio, and later films and television. Her most enduring impact was as one of network radio's more versatile actresses. Often appearing in 15 shows per week,<ref name=nyt/> comedies, dramas, thrillers, soap operas, and crime dramas, she became known as the \"First Lady of Radio\".\n\n==Early years==\nTuttle was born August 29, 1907, at Pleasant Lake, Indiana into a family with strong ties to entertainment. Her father, Clair Vivien Tuttle (1883\u20131950), had been a performer in [[minstrel show]]s before becoming a station agent for a railroad. Her grandfather, Frank Tuttle, managed an opera house and taught drama. Her mother was Verna Sylvia (Long) Tuttle. She discovered her own knack for acting after moving with her family to Glendale, Arizona. She later credited a drama coach there for \"making me aware of life as it really is\u2014by making me study life in real situations.\"<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last1=Thackrey|first1=Ted Jr.|title=Character Actress Lurene Tuttle, 78, Dies|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-05-30/local/me-8342_1_lurene-tuttle|accessdate=31 August 2015|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=May 30, 1986}}</ref>\n\nAfter her family moved to Southern California, Tuttle appeared in productions at the [[Pasadena Playhouse]], then joined the [[vaudeville]] troupe Murphy's Comedians. By the time of the [[Great Depression]], Tuttle had put her vocal versatility to work in radio, and within a decade, she became an in-demand actress in the medium.\n\n==Radio roles==\nTuttle's radio debut came in 1936 when she appeared on ''[[Hollywood Hotel (radio program)|Hollywood Hotel]]'' with [[Dick Powell]].<ref name=lat/> Despite having never performed before a microphone, Tuttle's audition won her a three-year contract with the program.<ref name=rtm847>{{cite journal|last1=Tuttle|first1=Lurene|title=Luck Is Hard Work|journal=Radio Mirror|date=August 1947|volume=28|issue=3|pages=20\u201321, 81\u201382|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Mirror/47/Mirror-1947-Aug.pdf|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThirteen years later, one newspaper columnist called her \"quite possibly the most-heard woman in America.\"<ref name=hn>{{cite news|last1=Handsaker|first1=Gene|title=Lurene Tuttle Probably Most-Heard Woman in U. S.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3131352/the_hutchinson_news/|agency=The Hutchinson News|date=October 26, 1949|page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 31, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nOn radio's ''[[The Adventures of Sam Spade]]'' she played just about every female role as well as Spade's secretary Effie Perrine.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|title=Lurene Tuttle, 79, an Actress In Films and on Radio and TV|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/05/31/obituaries/lurene-tuttle-79-an-actress-in-films-and-on-radio-and-tv.html|accessdate=31 August 2015|agency=New York Times|date=May 31, 1986}}</ref> She appeared in such shows as ''[[The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet]]'' and concurrently appeared on ''[[The Great Gildersleeve]]'' as the niece Marjorie Forrester. Tuttle had regular roles in such shows as ''Brenthouse'',<ref name=\"dunningota\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn |url-access=registration |quote=Brenthouse, serial drama. |last=Dunning |first=John |authorlink=John Dunning (detective fiction author) |title=On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio| date=1998| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=New York, NY| isbn=978-0-19-507678-3| page=[https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn/page/118 118] | edition=Revised| accessdate=2019-09-25}}</ref> ''[[Dr. Christian]]'', ''[[Duffy's Tavern]]'', ''[[One Man's Family]]'', ''[[The Raleigh Cigarette Program#The Red Skelton Show|The Red Skelton Show]]'' (as Junior's mother and as Daisy June, roles that she shared with Harriet Nelson), ''[[Hollywood Hotel (radio program)|Hollywood Hotel]]'', and ''Those We Love''.\n\n''[[Dr. Christian]]'' was unusual in that the show, according to critic [[Leonard Maltin]] in ''The Great American Broadcast: A Celebration of Radio's Golden Age'', solicited scripts from listeners (one of whom was a young [[Rod Serling]]) and put them on the air\u2014with a little help. Tuttle recalled:\n\n<blockquote>The real writers on the show had to fix them quite often a lot, because they were really quite amateurish. But they had nice thoughts, they had nice plots. They just needed fixing; the dialogue didn't work too well.</blockquote>\n\nTuttle guest starred on the radio police series ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]'', starring [[Jack Webb]], ''[[Lux Radio Theater]]'', ''[[The Screen Guild Theater]]'' and ''[[Suspense]]'', in the episode \"The Sisters\", with [[Rosalind Russell]]. In ''[[The Whistler]]'', she played good and evil twins and used separate microphones to stay in character for each twin.\n\nIt was during her time on ''Hollywood Hotel'' that Tuttle became involved in the founding of the [[American Federation of Television and Radio Artists|American Federation of Radio Artists]]. According to Maltin, Tuttle's male counterpart on the show, veteran actor [[Frank Nelson (actor)|Frank Nelson]] (a frequent guest performer on [[Jack Benny]]'s program), tried to get both a raise to $35 per show\u2014at a time when the show paid $5,000 per appearance to headlining guest stars. Nelson eventually got the raises, but the negotiations prompted him to become an AFRA co-founder and one of its active members.\n\nTuttle later became the first female president of the federation's Hollywood local.<ref name=lat/>\n\nTuttle also remembered the day the ''Hollywood Hotel'' sound effects man was upstaged by a Hollywood legend:\n\n<blockquote>The soundman was supposed to do a little yipping, yappy dog, like a terrier. He sounded like a Newfoundland dog or something, and the director kept saying \"That won't do.\" So [[Olivia de Havilland]] was sitting next to me, and she says \"I can do a very good dog.\" And I said \"Well, I don't think they'll let you do a dog. This is an audience show; you're a star, you can't do a dog.\" And Olivia says \"I'm going to do it.\" So she went over to the director, went into the booth and said \"I'd like to try doing this dog for you.\" So they put her behind the screen, and she went on the show and she did that yipping dog.\"</blockquote>\n\n== Films and television ==\nTuttle became a familiar face to millions of television viewers with more than 100 appearances from 1950 to 1986, often in the role of an inquisitive busybody. On television and in films, Tuttle streamlined herself into a pattern of roles between wise, loving wives/mothers or bristling matrons. She was familiar to the early television audience as wife/mother Lavinia (Vinnie) Day in ''[[Life with Father#Television series|Life with Father]]'' (1953\u20131955). Columnist [[Hedda Hopper]] called the selection of [[Leon Ames]] as Father and Tuttle as Mother \"what I consider 22 carat casting with two all-Americans.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hopper|first1=Hedda|title=Producer Crosses Sea to Sign Cary Grant|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1953/10/07/page/38/article/looking-at-hollywood|accessdate=1 September 2015|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=October 7, 1953|page=Part 3, Page 6}}</ref>\n\n''[[Heaven Only Knows (1947 film)|Heaven Only Knows]]'' (1947) was her first film.<ref name=lat/> She went on to roles in other films such as [[Orson Welles]]'s ''[[Macbeth (1948 film)|Macbeth]]'' (1948), ''[[Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House]]'' (1948) and [[Alfred Hitchcock|Alfred Hitchcock's]] ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960), as the wife of Sheriff Chambers. In ''[[Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1952) she portrayed a mother who lets a disturbed [[Marilyn Monroe]] babysit her daughter. The next year she appeared again with Marilyn in ''[[Niagara (film)|Niagara]]'', as Mrs. Kettering. She had a rare starring role in ''[[Ma Barker's Killer Brood]]'' (1960). She played Grandma Pusser in the original ''[[Walking Tall (1973 film)|Walking Tall]]'' film trilogy, and also appeared in horror films such as ''[[The Manitou]]'' (1978), starring [[Tony Curtis]]. Her final film role was in the 1983 film ''[[Testament (1983 film)|Testament]]''.\n\nShe guest-starred twice on [[Edmond O'Brien]]'s 1960 crime drama ''[[Johnny Midnight (TV series)|Johnny Midnight]]''. She then played a supporting role in the 1961 ''[[Father of the Bride (TV series)|Father of the Bride]]'' television [[situation comedy]]. She made six guest appearances on ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', with [[Raymond Burr]], during the nine-year run of the show from 1957 to 1966. She usually played the role of the defendant, such as Anna Houser in \"The Case of the Substitute Face\" in 1958, Sarette Winslow in \"The Case of the Artful Dodger\" in 1959, Sarah Breel in \"The Case of the Shoplifter's Shoe\" in 1963, and Josephine Kempton in \"The Case of the Grinning Gorilla\" in 1965. However, in 1966 she played the role of murderess Henny McLeod in \"The Case of the Avenging Angel.\"\n\nIn 1958 and 1959, she was cast in two episodes as Gladys Purvis, the mother of series character Kate McCoy, played by [[Kathleen Nolan]], in the sitcom ''[[The Real McCoys]]'', with [[Walter Brennan]] and [[Richard Crenna]].<ref name=imdb>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0878354/|title=Lurene Tuttle|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref> She appeared twice on the NBC western series ''[[The Californians (TV series)|The Californians]]'', once as Belle Calhoun in \"Skeleton in the Closet\" (1958) and then as Maude Sorel in \"The Painted Lady\" (1959). She guest-starred with [[Andrew Duggan]] in his crime series ''[[Bourbon Street Beat]]''.\n\nTuttle appeared three times each on sitcoms ''[[The Danny Thomas Show]]'' and ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'' and twice on the following: ''[[Leave It to Beaver]]'', ''[[The Bob Cummings Show]]'', ''[[The Ann Sothern Show]]'', ''[[Pete and Gladys]]'', ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'', ''[[Hazel (TV series)|Hazel]]'', ''[[General Electric Theater]]'', ''[[Switch (TV series)|Switch]]'', and ''[[Fantasy Island (1977 TV series)|Fantasy Island]]''. \n \nIn 1960, she was cast as Mrs. Courtland in the episode \"The Raffle Ticket\" of the sitcom based on the [[comic strip]] ''[[Dennis the Menace (1959 TV series)|Dennis the Menace]]'', with [[Jay North]] and [[Joseph Kearns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0557993/|title=The Raffle Ticket'', ''Dennis the Menace'', December 18, 1960|publisher=Internet Movie Data Base|accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTuttle guest-starred in such westerns as ''[[Buckskin (TV series)|Buckskin]]'', ''[[The Restless Gun]]'', ''[[Colt .45 (TV series)|Colt .45]]'', ''[[Johnny Ringo (TV series)|Johnny Ringo]]'' as well as ''[[The Cowboys (TV series)|The Cowboys]]'', ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'', ''[[Bonanza]]'', ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Jim Bowie]]'', ''[[Lawman (TV series)|Lawman]]'', and ''[[The Iron Horse (TV series)|The Iron Horse]].''<ref name=imdb/>\n\nTuttle was cast as Mrs. Grange in the 1963 episode \"The Risk\" on the drama series ''[[Mr. Novak]]'', starring [[James Franciscus]] as an idealistic high school teacher. She later appeared on the popular 1960s sitcoms ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'', ''[[The Munsters]]'', and ''[[Petticoat Junction]]''.\n\nTuttle's best-known role to the general public was in 32 episodes of the series ''[[Julia (TV series)|Julia]]'' (1968\u20131971) as the humorless but warm-hearted Hannah Yarby.<ref name=imdb/>\n\nIn 1972, she appeared as Bella Swann on the episode \"Farmer Ted and the News\" on \"The Mary Tyler Moore Show\" and as Mrs. Sharp on \"The Partridge Family\"\nthat same year.\n\nIn 1980, Tuttle appeared as Mrs. McIntyre in the television movie ''[[White Mama]]'', with [[Bette Davis]].<ref name=\"imdb\" /> From 1981 to 1984, Tuttle appeared six times on the drama series ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]''\n\nIn 1985, Tuttle appeared in episode 25 (\"Murder in the Afternoon\") of ''Murder, She Wrote'', playing the character Agnes Cochran, Jessica Fletcher's aunt.  The episode first aired on October 13, 1985.\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 1944, Tuttle received Radio Life magazine's Distinguished Achievement Award for Best Supporting Feminine Player.<ref>{{cite news|title=Distinguished Achievement Awards|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/Archive-Radio-Life-IDX/IDX/Radio-Life-1944-04-09-OCR-Page-0014.pdf|accessdate=1 September 2015|agency=Radio Life|date=April 9, 1944}}</ref>\n\nTuttle has two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] \u2013 \"Star of Radio\" at 1760 Vine Street and \"Star of Television\" at 7011 Hollywood Boulevard. Both stars were dedicated February 8, 1960.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lurene Tuttle|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/lurene-tuttle|website=Hollywood Walk of Fame|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life ==\nTuttle married [[Melville Ruick]], an actor whom she had met during her radio years; the couple had a daughter, [[Barbara Ruick]],.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mother and Daughter Suggest Beauty Tips|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3124933/the_paris_news/|agency=The Paris News|date=December 19, 1955|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 30, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> Tuttle and Ruick eventually divorced. She married Frederick W. Cole, an engineer, on November 27, 1950 in Pasadena, California; she sued him for divorce on January 4, 1956.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lurene Tuttle Sues for Divorce|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3131273/long_beach_independent/|agency=Long Beach Independent|date=January 5, 1956|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 31, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> Daughter Barbara Ruick, 43, who was married to film composer [[John Williams]], died of a cerebral hemorrhage while on film location in 1974.\n\nShe became a respected acting coach and teacher\u2014something she had always done, even at the height of her acting career (she often re-trained radio actors who had been away from the craft during service in World War II).\n\nTuttle had a hobby of collecting toy dogs. A 1930 newspaper article reported \"Her dressing room shelf is filled with more than 200 miniature replicas of every variety of dog known.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Toy Dogs, Not Real Ones, Are Actress' Hobby|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3131496/oakland_tribune/|agency=Oakland Tribune|date=May 6, 1930|page=27|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = August 31, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nTuttle, a registered [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], campaigned for [[Dwight Eisenhower]] in the [[1952 United States presidential election|1952 presidential election]].<ref>''Motion Picture and Television Magazine'', November 1952, page 34, Ideal Publishers </ref>\n\n==Death==\nTuttle died from cancer May 28, 1986 at Encino Hospital. Memorial services were held June 2, 1986 at Church of the Recessional at Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Glendale.<ref name=lat/>\n\nHer ''Sam Spade'' co-star [[Howard Duff]], who delivered her eulogy, remembered Tuttle:\n\n<blockquote>She could just take hold of a part and do something with it...I think she never met a part she didn't like. She just loved to work; she loved to act. She's a woman who was born to do what she was doing and loved every minute of it.</blockquote>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{div col}}\n*''[[Stand Up and Cheer!]]'' (1934) \u2013 Stenographer (uncredited)\n*''[[Tom, Dick and Harry (1941 film)|Tom, Dick and Harry]]'' (1941) \u2013 Girl Lead in Movie (voice, uncredited)\n*''[[Heaven Only Knows (1947 film)|Heaven Only Knows]]'' (1947) \u2013 Mrs. O'Donnell\n*''[[Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House]]'' (1948) \u2013 Mary\n*''[[Homecoming (1948 film)|Homecoming]]'' (1948) \u2013 Miss Stoker\n*''[[Macbeth (1948 film)|Macbeth]]'' (1948) \u2013 Gentlewoman / The Three\n*''[[The Admiral Was a Lady]]'' (1950) \u2013 Ethyl \u2013 Unemployment Clerk (uncredited)\n*''[[A Life of Her Own]]'' (1950) \u2013 Secretary (uncredited)\n*''[[Watch the Birdie (1950 film)|Watch the Birdie]]'' (1950) \u2013 Millie (uncredited)\n*''[[Goodbye, My Fancy]]'' (1951) \u2013 Ellen Griswold\n*''[[Tomorrow Is Another Day (1951 American film)|Tomorrow Is Another Day]]'' (1951) \u2013 Stella Dawson\n*''[[The Whip Hand]]'' (1951) \u2013 Molly Loomis\n*''[[Room for One More (film)|Room for One More]]'' (1952) \u2013 Miss Kenyon\n*''[[Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1952) \u2013 Ruth Jones\n*''[[Niagara (film)|Niagara]]'' (1953) \u2013 Mrs. Kettering\n*''[[Never Wave at a WAC]]'' (1953) \u2013 Capt. Murchinson, Company CO\n*''[[The Affairs of Dobie Gillis]]'' (1953) \u2013 Mrs. Eleanor Hammer\n*''[[Give a Girl a Break]]'' (1953) \u2013 Mrs. Doolittle\n*''[[The Glass Slipper]]'' (1955) \u2013 Cousin Loulou\n*''[[Sincerely Yours (film)|Sincerely Yours]]'' (1955) \u2013 Mrs. McGinley\n*''[[Slander (1956 film)|Slander]]'' (1957) \u2013 Mrs. Doyle\n*''[[Untamed Youth]]'' (1957) \u2013 Judge Cecilia Steele Tropp\n*''[[Sweet Smell of Success]]'' (1957) \u2013 Loretta Bartha (uncredited)\n*''[[Ma Barker's Killer Brood]]'' (1960) \u2013 Ma Barker\n*''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960) \u2013 Mrs. Chambers\n*''[[Critic's Choice (film)|Critic's Choice]]'' (1963) \u2013 Mother in \"Sisters Three\"\n*''[[Nightmare in the Sun]]'' (1965) \u2013 Gideon's wife\n*''The Restless Ones'' (1965)\n*''[[The Ghost and Mr. Chicken]]'' (1966) \u2013 Mrs. Natalie Miller\n*''[[The Fortune Cookie]]'' (1966) \u2013 Mother Hinkle\n*''[[The Horse in the Gray Flannel Suit]]'' (1968) \u2013 Aunt Martha\n*''[[Walking Tall (1973 film)|Walking Tall]]'' (1973) \u2013 Grandma\n*''Dirty Duck'' (1974) \u2013 Duck's Mother (voice)\n*''[[Walking Tall Part 2]]'' (1975) \u2013 Grandma Pusser\n*''The World Through the Eyes of Children'' (1975) \u2013 Tuttle\n*''[[Evil Town]]'' (1977) \u2013 Mildred Phelps\n*''[[Walking Tall: Final Chapter]]'' (1977) \u2013 Grandma Pusser\n*''[[The Manitou]]'' (1978) \u2013 Mrs. Herz\n*''The Story of Heidi'' (1979) - Clara's Grandmother (voice)\n*''[[Nutcracker Fantasy]]'' (1979) \u2013 Aunt Gerda (voice)\n*''[[Parts: The Clonus Horror]]'' (1979) \u2013 Anna Noble\n*''[[Human Experiments]]'' (1979) \u2013 Granny\n*''[[White Mama]]'' (1980) \u2013 Mrs. McIntyre\n*''[[Return of the Beverly Hillbillies]]'' (1981) \u2013 Mollie Heller\n*''[[Testament (1983 film)|Testament]]'' (1983) \u2013 Rosemary Abhart\n*''[[It Came Upon the Midnight Clear (film)|It Came Upon the Midnight Clear]]'' (1984) \u2013 Mrs. Hunt\n{{div col end}}\n\nShe also played the part of Eddie Haskell's landlady in ''[[Leave It to Beaver]]''{{'}}s 1962 episode called \"Bachelor at Large\".\n\n== Records ==\nTuttle played the swallow in \"[[The Happy Prince (Orson Welles, Bing Crosby album)|The Happy Prince]]\", an adaption of Oscar Wilde's short story with [[Orson Welles]] and [[Bing Crosby]] (1946). The story had been adapted for radio by Orson Welles in 1944, featuring a musical score by [[Bernard Herrmann]]. It aired on the Philco Radio Hall of Fame broadcast on December 24, 1944<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pairpoint|first1=Lionel|title=And Here's Bing|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/afrs.htm#sundry46|website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> with Lureen Tuttle playing The Swallow and featuring Bing Crosby alongside Orson Welles, with Herrmann's music conducted by [[Victor Young]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Indiana|California|Theatre|Radio|Film|Television}}\n\n==References==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== General references ===\n* Frank Buxton and Bill Owen, ''The Big Broadcast 1920\u20131950''.\n* Leonard Maltin, ''The Great American Broadcast: A Celebration of Radio's Golden Age''. New York: Dutton, 1997.\n* [[Gerald Nachman (journalist)|Gerald Nachman]], ''Raised on Radio''. New York: Pantheon, 1998.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p4.cgi?ArtistName=Tuttle,%20Lurene&ArtistNumber=29861 From radioGOLDINdex: a partial list of radio programs in which Lurene Tuttle appeared]\n* {{IMDb name|878354}}\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0DE1D61F3EF932A05756C0A960948260 ''New York Times'' obituary]\n\n=== Audio ===\n* [https://archive.org/download/GG_S_01/GG_1941-09-07_ep002_Marjories_Cake.mp3 ''The Great Gildersleeve'', \"Marjorie's Cake\" (7 September 1941)]\n* 